				\begin{document}$${\rm{BAI}}={\rm{\pi }}\times ({R}_{n}^{2}-{R}_{n-1}^{2})$$\end{document}BAI=π×(Rn2−Rn−12)where R is the radius at breast height and n is the year of tree-ring formation. We measured tree-ring width of 35 cores included 12 tree-ring cores more than 150 years older. We calculated BAI with the beginning width in 1855 calendar year, then we gave up the first 25 years data of each core considering the less number of sample cores and “juvenile age effects” might rise the errors of tree-ring widths (similar consideration applied to the analysis of tree-ring δ13C)13. Then we calculated the BAI between 1880 to 2014 of each tree.

